  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">LTI & Learning Standards</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
      <strong>LTI (Learning Tools Interoperability)</strong> is the standard that allows learning tools to plug into LMS platforms. If you use external content libraries, assessment tools, or virtual classrooms, LTI support determines how seamlessly they integrate. <strong>Moodle</strong> has the most mature LTI implementation, supporting both LTI 1.1 as a tool provider and consumer, plus LTI 1.3 and Advantage services.
    </p>
    <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
      <strong>Docebo</strong>, <strong>Absorb</strong>, <strong>TalentLMS</strong>, and <strong>LearnWorlds</strong> all support LTI to varying degrees, typically as LTI consumers (embedding external tools). <strong>Expert-focused platforms</strong> (Thinkific, Kajabi, Teachable, Podia) do not support LTI — they focus on direct content creation rather than integrating external learning tools.
    </p>
    <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
      For academic institutions and corporate training departments using specialized content libraries or assessment tools, LTI support is essential. For experts creating original content, it's irrelevant.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Webhooks & API Quality</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
      When pre-built integrations don't exist, APIs and webhooks enable custom connections. <strong>Thinkific</strong>, <strong>Teachable</strong>, <strong>LearnWorlds</strong>, and <strong>Kajabi</strong> all offer well-documented REST APIs with webhook support for real-time event notification. The documentation quality and rate limits vary — Thinkific and LearnWorlds are particularly developer-friendly.
    </p>
    <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
      <strong>Enterprise platforms</strong> (Docebo, Absorb) provide comprehensive APIs designed for enterprise integration scenarios. These APIs support bulk operations, sophisticated filtering, and enterprise security requirements. <strong>TalentLMS</strong> offers a simple but capable API suitable for most automation needs.
    </p>
    <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
      <strong>Moodle</strong> provides the most extensive API surface through its Web Services layer, supporting REST, SOAP, and XML-RPC. Nearly any Moodle operation can be performed via API, making it the most flexible platform for custom integration — though this flexibility requires development expertise. <strong>Podia</strong> has the most limited API of the major platforms, reflecting its focus on simplicity over extensibility.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">The Bottom Line</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
      Integration strategy should match your operational reality. If you're running a learning business connected to marketing automation and payment processing, expert-focused platforms offer better native integrations for your use case. If you're deploying enterprise training integrated with HRIS, CRM, and identity management, enterprise platforms provide the connectors and security standards you need.
    </p>
    <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
      The trap is assuming more integrations equals better integration support. A platform with 200 shallow connectors often creates more frustration than one with 20 deep, well-maintained integrations. Evaluate the specific tools you use, not the connector count. And remember — APIs turn any platform into an integration platform; the question is whether you have the resources to use them.
    </p>
  </section>

